08266nam a22010695i 9780824884192DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020022812  a97808248841927 a10.1515/97808248841922doi  a(DE-B1597)537289  a(OCoLC)1183955325  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI00aBL2525b.E58 2020 4aBL2525b.E58 2020eb 7aSOC0430002bisacsh04a200.89/9507322300aEnvisioning Religion, Race, and Asian Americans /ced. by David K. Yoo, Khyati Y. Joshi, Russell Leong, David K. Yoo. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b1 b&w illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIntersections: Asian and Pacific American Transcultural Studies ;v4500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Reflections of the Past and Present -- t1. Reconstructing Asian America’s Religious Past -- t2. Asian American Religious Beliefs Reconsidered -- tPart II. Glimpses of Religion and Empire -- t3. Outsider Citizens within the US Empire: Muslim Youth, Race, Religion, and Identity -- t4. American Apartheid for the New Millennium: The Racialization and Repression of Asian American Religious Minorities -- t5. Where the History Books End: Religion and Vietnamese America in the Afterlife of the Vietnam War -- tPart III. Revealing Religious Formations -- t6. The Gospel According to Rice: The Next Asian American Christianity -- t7. Postscript: (Re)Thinking and (Re)Creating Asian American Christianities through a Gospel According to (Fried) Rice? -- t8. Modernity in the Service of Tradition: Women and Gender within Hinduism in the United States -- t9. Life in the Fishbowl: An Asian American Autobiographical Theological Reflection -- tPart IV. Visualizing Subjectivities -- t10. Learning Hinduism through Comics and Popular Culture -- t11. Queer Asian American Theologies -- t12. The Roots of Chinese American Religious Nones: Continuities with the Liyi Tradition -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Envisioning Religion, Race, and Asian Americans, David K. Yoo and Khyati Y. Joshi assemble a wide-ranging and important collection of essays documenting the intersections of race and religion and Asian American communities—a combination so often missing both in the scholarly literature and in public discourse. Issues of religion and race/ethnicity undergird current national debates around immigration, racial profiling, and democratic freedoms, but these issues, as the contributors document, are longstanding ones in the United States.The essays feature dimensions of traditions such as Islam, Hinduism, and Sikhism, as well as how religion engages with topics that include religious affiliation (or lack thereof), the legacy of the Vietnam War, and popular culture. The contributors also address the role of survey data, pedagogy, methodology, and literature that is richly complementary and necessary for understanding the scope and range of the subject of Asian American religions. These essays attest to the vibrancy and diversity of Asian American religions, while at the same time situating these conversations in a scholarly lineage and discourse. This collection will certainly serve as an invaluable resource for scholars, students, and general readers with interests in Asian American religions in fields such as ethnic and Asian American studies, religious studies, American studies, and related fields that focus on immigration and race.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAsian AmericansxRace identity. 0aAsian AmericansxReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAli, Arshad